 This problem is equivalent to finding the number of ways of selecting one $x$ term in each of the binomials at the expansion so that their product yields (\textit{i.e.}, has coefficient one}) one negative and two positive terms, as $$(1+x_1)(1+x_2)\dotsm(1+x_n)$$ has coefficient one if the product contains one negative term or all the $x_n$ terms, and has coefficient zero if all the $x_n$ terms have been canceled with each other. I thought in how many ways we could invest two negative terms from among the first eight negative terms, then multiply it by the number of ways that one positive of the $14$ terms could be chosen. </think> My workings: As $x$ is only raised to the power of 2 in the binomial formula, the number of ways of choosing one negative and two positive terms from the given  binomials is $14 \choose 2$. Then there are 8 ways to choose two negative terms in the first eight binomials. Hence the answer = $8{14 \choose 2}$. 
